INSERT INTO `questionsat` VALUES (1,'You are solving a maze puzzle, trying to find your way through a labyrinth of passages. Which of the following algorithms describes your approach?','a) Keep moving forward until you hit a dead end. Then, backtrack\r\nto the last junction and try a different path.','b)  Randomly choose passages at each junction until you find the exit.','c) Always turn right at each junction and follow the right wall\r\nuntil you reach the exit.','d) Keep a map of the maze in your mind and calculate the\r\nshortest path to the exit at each junction.',NULL,3),(2,'You are trying to solve a Sudoku puzzle. Which of the following algorithms best represents your strategy?','a) Fill in the first empty cell you encounter with a number that doesn\'t\r\nviolate any rules. Repeat until the puzzle is complete.','b) Randomly assign numbers to empty cells until the puzzle is complete.','c) Start with the number 1 and try placing it in each empty cell\r\nuntil you find a valid solution. Repeat with the next number until\r\nthe puzzle is complete.','d) Analyze the entire puzzle at once, identifying which numbers can\r\ngo in each cell based on the current state of the board.',NULL,4),(3,'You are playing a game where you need to guess a secret number between 1 and 100. After each guess, you are told\r\nwhether your guess is higher or lower than the secret number. Which of the following algorithms describes your\r\nguessing strategy?','a) Start with 50 and adjust your guess up or down based on the feedback\r\nuntil you find the secret number.','b) Randomly guess a number between 1 and 100 each time\r\nuntil you find the secret number.','c) Always guess the same number and increment it by 1 after each\r\nincorrect guess until you find the secret number.','d) Use a binary search algorithm to systematically narrow down\r\nthe possible range of the secret number with each guess.',NULL,1),(4,'You are packing items into a suitcase, trying to fit in as many items as possible without exceeding the weight limit.\r\nWhich of the following algorithms describes your packing strategy?','a) Start with the heaviest item and add it to the suitcase. Then, sequentially\r\nadd the next heaviest items until the weight limit is reached.','b) Randomly select items and attempt to fit them into the suitcase\r\nuntil it is full.','c) Sort the items by size and try to fit in as many smaller items\r\nas possible before adding larger items.','d) Calculate the space remaining in the suitcase after each addition and\r\nprioritize items that best fill the remaining space without exceeding the\r\nweight limit.',NULL,4),(5,'You are studying for an exam with multiple chapters. Which of the following algorithms describes your study approach?','a) Start with the first chapter and study it thoroughly before moving\r\non to the next chapter.','b) Randomly select chapters to study until you cover all of them.','c) Study the chapters in reverse order, beginning with the last\r\nchapter and working your way to the first.','d) Allocate study time to each chapter based on its importance\r\nand difficulty, focusing more on challenging chapters.',NULL,4),(6,'You are trying to organize a list of tasks based on their priority levels. Which of the following algorithms best represents\r\nyour task prioritization strategy?','a) Assign a priority number to each task and sort them in ascending\r\norder. Start with the task of lowest priority and work your way up.','b) Randomly select tasks to work on until all tasks are completed.','c) Begin with the task that has the highest priority and work your way\r\ndown the list.','d) Group tasks based on their types and tackle all tasks within each\r\ngroup before moving on to the next group.',NULL,3),(7,'You are planting a garden with different types of flowers. Which of the following algorithms describes your planting strategy?','a) Start with one type of flower and plant it throughout the garden\r\nbefore moving on to the next type','b) Randomly scatter seeds of different flower types in the garden.','c) Alternate between planting different types of flowers in rows or sections\r\nof the garden.','d) Plant flowers based on their sunlight and soil requirements,\r\ngrouping together those with similar needs.',NULL,4),(8,'You are playing a game of chess against an opponent. Which of the following algorithms describes your strategy for making moves?','a) Randomly select a legal move each turn until the game is over.','b) Always move your pieces forward aggressively, aiming to capture your\r\nopponent\'s pieces whenever possible.','c) Analyze the board to identify your opponent\'s threats and\r\npotential moves, and choose your own moves accordingly.','d) Focus on protecting your own pieces without considering \r\nyour opponent\'s moves, relying on luck to win the game.',NULL,3),(9,'You are writing an essay for a class assignment. Which of the following algorithms best represents your approach to writing the essay?','a) Start with the introduction, then write each body paragraph in\r\norder before finishing with the conclusion.','b) Randomly write sections of the essay until all points are covered,\r\nthen rearrange them into a coherent structure.','c) Begin with the conclusion and work backward, outlining the\r\nmain points before filling in the details.','d) Write the body paragraphs first, then craft the introduction\r\nand conclusion based on the content of the essay.',NULL,1),(10,'You are preparing a shopping list for groceries. Which of the following algorithms describes your method of creating the list?','a) Write down items in the order they come to mind, without any specific organization.','b)  Randomly select items from a list until all needed items are included','c) Group items by category (e.g., dairy, produce, pantry) and\r\nlist them in each category before moving to the next.','d) Start with the last item you need and work backward until you\r\nreach the first item on your list.',NULL,3),(11,'You are solving a Rubik\'s Cube puzzle. Which of the following algorithms describes your approach to solving it?','a) Randomly twist the cube\'s faces until it is solved.','b) Start with one face and solve it completely before moving\r\nto the next face.','c) Apply a set sequence of moves repeatedly until the cube is solved.','d) Analyze the current state of the cube and determine the optimal\r\nsequence of moves to solve it.',NULL,3),(12,'You are trying to learn a new language. Which of the following algorithms best represents your language learning strategy?','a) Focus on memorizing vocabulary words before attempting to\r\nlearn grammar rules.','b) Randomly study different aspects of the language without\r\nany particular order.','c) Start with basic grammar and sentence structure before\r\ngradually adding vocabulary.','d) Immerse yourself in conversations and reading materials in\r\nthe language, learning through context and exposure.',NULL,4),(13,'You are organizing your bookshelf. Which of the following algorithms describes your method of arranging books?','a) Randomly place books on the shelf without any specific order.','b) Arrange books alphabetically by title or author\'s last name.','c) Group books by genre or subject and arrange them within\r\neach group based on size or color.','d) Sort books by size and place them on the shelf in\r\nascending or descending order.',NULL,2),(14,'You are preparing for a long-distance road trip. Which of the following algorithms describes your route planning strategy?','a) Choose the shortest route from your current location to the destination\r\nwithout considering other factors.','b) Randomly select roads to take until you reach the destination.','c) Plan the route based on landmarks or points of \r\nnterest along the way.','d) Use a GPS or mapping software to find the fastest or most\r\nscenic route to the destination.',NULL,4),(15,'You are trying to solve a complex math problem. Which of the following algorithms best represents your problem-solving approach?','a) Start with the solution and work backward to determine the\r\nsteps needed to reach it.','b) Randomly try different mathematical operations until the\r\nproblem is solved.','c) Break the problem down into smaller, more manageable parts\r\nand solve each part sequentially.','d) Apply a specific problem-solving technique or theorem that\r\nis known to be effective for similar problems.',NULL,3),(16,'You are cleaning your room, which is cluttered with various items. Which of the following algorithms describes your cleaning strategy?','a) Begin by organizing items by type (e.g., clothes, books, electronics)\r\nand then clean each category one by one.','b) Randomly pick up items and put them away until the room is tidy.','c) Start from one corner of the room and work your way\r\nmethodically to\r\nthe opposite corner, cleaning as you go.','d) Clean whichever area of the room catches your attention first,\r\nmoving on to other areas as you see fit.',NULL,1),(17,'You are trying to solve a jigsaw puzzle. Which of the following algorithms best represents your puzzle-solving strategy?','a)  Start with the corners and edges, then fill in the middle pieces\r\nto complete the puzzle.','b) Randomly select pieces and attempt to fit them together until\r\nthe puzzle is complete.','c) Sort pieces by color or pattern and assemble them in groups\r\nbefore connecting the groups to complete the puzzle.','d) Begin with the largest or most distinctive sections of the puzzle and\r\ngradually add smaller pieces to fill in the gaps.',NULL,1),(18,'You are learning to play a musical instrument. Which of the following algorithms describes your practice routine?','a) Start with simple exercises and gradually increase difficulty\r\nas you improve.','b) Randomly practice different pieces or techniques each session.','c) Focus on mastering one piece or technique at a time before\r\nmoving on to the next.','d) Alternate between practicing scales, chords, and songs in\r\nno particular order.',NULL,4),(19,'You are trying to solve a crossword puzzle. Which of the following algorithms describes your approach to solving it?','a) Begin with the longest words and fill them in first, then work on\r\nshorter words that intersect with them.','b) Randomly fill in words until the puzzle is complete.','c) Start with the words you know for certain and use their\r\nletters to help solve other clues.','d) Solve clues in sequential order, moving across and down the puzzle grid.',NULL,3),(20,'You are cooking a multi-course meal for a dinner party. Which of the following algorithms best represents your meal preparation strategy?','a) Start with the main course and work backward to prepare appetizers\r\nand desserts.','b) Randomly select dishes to prepare until you have a complete menu.','c) Plan the menu based on cooking times and ingredient availability,\r\npreparing dishes in a logical order to ensure everything is ready at the same time.','d) Prepare each dish as inspiration strikes, without any specific\r\norder or plan in mind.',NULL,3),(21,'Pacman is starting at position A5 on the grid. Which instructions will take Pacman along the path to reach the Ghost located at position A1?','a) Turn right, turn right, move forward, move forward, move forward,\r\nmove forward, turn right.','b) Turn right, turn right, move forward, move forward,\r\nmove forward, move forward, turn right, turn right.','c) Move forward, move forward, turn right,\r\nmove forward, move forward, move forward,\r\nmove forward, turn left, move forward, move forward.','d) Move forward, move forward, turn right, move forward,\r\nmove forward, move forward, move forward, turn right,\r\nmove forward, move forward.','at21.png',4),(22,'What is the output of the pseudo code?\r\nSET x to 5\r\nSET y to 3\r\nSET z to x + y\r\nOUTPUT z','a) 3','b) 5','c) 8','d) 15',NULL,3),(23,'What is the output of the pseudo code?\r\nSET a to 6\r\nSET b to 4\r\nIF a > b THEN\r\n      OUTPUT \"a is greater than b\"\r\nELSE\r\n      OUTPUT \"b is greater than or equal to a\"','a) a is greater than b','b) b is greater than a','c) a is equal to b','d) b is greater than or equal to a',NULL,1),(24,'What is the purpose of an algorithm?','a) To execute code directly  ','b) To solve a problem step by step  ','c) To design user interfaces  ','d) To store data  ',NULL,2),(25,'Which of the following is NOT a characteristic of a good algorithm?','a) Clear and well-defined steps','b) Uses complex mathematical formulas','c) Can be easily understood by others','d) Solves the problem efficiently',NULL,2),(26,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\r\nInitialize Integer x, y, z\r\nSet y = 1, x = 2\r\nz = x ^ y\r\nPrint z','a) 1','b) 2','c) 4','d) 3[^1^][1]',NULL,2),(27,'Imagine a program needs to find the highest score among a list of exam grades. Which of the following best describes this search algorithm?','a) Start with the first grade and compare it to every other grade.\r\nIf it\'s higher, keep it as the highest. Repeat until all grades are compared.','b) Ask the user to manually identify the highest grade.','c) Add all the grades together and then divide by the number\r\nof grades (average score).','d) Randomly pick a grade and assume it\'s the highest.\r\nIf you find a higher one later, replace it.',NULL,1),(28,'Imagine a social media app wants to display only the posts from your friends. Which of the following best describes part of the algorithm?','a) Show all posts from everyone and let the user manually hide\r\nunfriend\'s posts.','b) Check each post individually to see if the author is your friend.','c) Create a list of your friends and only show posts from people on that list.','d) Display a random selection of posts regardless of the author.\n',NULL,3),(29,'A program needs to recommend movies to a user based on their past viewing history. How can the algorithm improve its recommendations over time?','a) Keep showing the same movies the user has already watched.','b) Store user data and analyze watch history to suggest similar\r\nmovies.','c) Completely ignore past watch history and suggest random movies.','d) Force the user to pick movies from a pre-defined list.',NULL,2),(30,'How can understanding algorithmic thinking be helpful in daily life, even outside of computer science?','a) It allows you to write complex computer programs.','b) It helps you break down complex problems into smaller,\r\nmanageable steps.','c) It forces you to memorize a lot of technical terms.','d) It\'s only useful for professional programmers.',NULL,2),(31,'It\'s only useful for professional programmers.','a) Move the robot randomly in different directions until it finds the exit.','b) Explore the maze systematically, keeping track of visited paths\r\nto avoid getting lost.','c) Ask the user for maze instructions and follow them precisely.','d) The robot cannot navigate a maze without human intervention.',NULL,2),(32,'You\'re writing a program to check if a number is divisible by 3. Which approach is the MOST efficient?','a) Divide the number by 3 and check for a remainder of 0.','b) Subtract 3 repeatedly from the number until it becomes negative.\r\nIf it\'s exactly 0 after subtractions, it\'s divisible by 3.','c) List all multiples of 3 and compare the target number to the list.','d) There\'s no efficient way to check divisibility by 3.',NULL,1),(33,'A flowchart is a useful tool for representing the steps involved in an algorithm. What does a diamond shape typically represent in a flowchart?','a) The start or end of the algorithm.','b) An input or output operation.','c) A decision point with multiple possible paths.','d) A complex mathematical calculation.',NULL,3),(34,'Imagine a program that recommends movies based on your watch history.  Which factor is LEAST relevant to the recommendation algorithm?','a) The genre of movies you previously watched.','b) he ratings you gave to previous movies.','c) The release date of the movies you watched.','d) The actors or directors in common between movies you\r\nwatched and recommended ones.',NULL,3),(35,'How can understanding algorithmic thinking be helpful when debugging a computer program that\'s not working correctly?','a) It allows you to write complex error messages for users.','b)  It helps you break down the program\'s logic step by\r\nstep to identify where the error might occur.','c) It requires memorizing a lot of programming syntax.','d) It\'s only useful for professional programmers.',NULL,2),(36,'You\'re writing a program to calculate the average of a list of numbers. Which of the following best represents this algorithm using pseudocode?','a) Set a variable \"total\" to 0. Loop through each number in the list,\r\nadding it to the \"total\". After the loop, divide \"total\" by the\r\nnumber\r\nof elements in the list.','b) Add all the numbers in the list together and divide by a random number.','c) Manually calculate the average based on a formula without an algorithm.','d) Ask the user to enter the average of the numbers in the list.',NULL,1),(37,'Imagine a program that needs to compress a file to save storage space. Which of the following best describes a core concept of compression algorithms?','a) Adding decorative borders around the file icon.','b) Identifying and removing redundant data patterns within the file.','c) Converting the file to a different format with a smaller file size (but potentially losing quality).','d) Asking the user to manually delete unnecessary parts of the file.',NULL,2),(38,'Which instructions will take Pacman to the Ghost located at position C3?','a) Move forward, move forward, turn left, turn right, turn left.','b) Turn right, turn right, turn left, move forward, move forward.','c) Move forward, move forward, turn left, move forward,\r\nmove forward.','d) Move forward, move forward, turn right, move forward, move forward.','at38.png',3),(39,'Which instructions take the \"Pacman\" (B6) to the \"Ghost\" (B4) using the path marked out?','a) Move forward (3x), turn right, move forward (3x), turn right,\r\nmove forward (3x), turn right, move forward.','b) Move forward (2x), turn right, move forward (2x),\r\nturn right, move forward (2x), turn right, move forward.','c) Move forward (4x), turn left, move forward (4x),\r\nturn left, move forward (4x), turn left, move forward.','d) Move forward (3x), turn left, move forward (3x), turn\r\nleft, move forward (3x), turn left, move forward.','at39.png',1),(40,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\nInitialize Integer a, b, c\nSet a = 3, b = 2\nc = a * b\nPrint c','a) 3','b) 2','c) 5','d) 6',NULL,4),(41,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\nInitialize Integer x, y, z\n    Set x = 5, y = 2\n    z = x / y\n    Print z','a) 3','b) 2','c) 2.5','d) 2.0',NULL,3),(42,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\nInitialize Integer x, y, z\n    Set x = 4, y = 3\n   z = x % y\n   Print z','a) 1','b) 0','c) 3','d) 12',NULL,1),(43,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\n    Initialize Integer a, b, c\n    Set a = 4, b = 2\n   c = a - b\n    Print c','a) 2','b) 4','c) -2','d) 6',NULL,1),(44,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\n    Initialize Integer x, y, z\n    Set x = 6, y = 2\n    z = x + y\n    Print z','a) 6','b) 2','c) 8','d) 12',NULL,3),(45,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\nInitialize Integer a, b, c\n    Set a = 7, b = 3\n    c = a / b\n    Print c','a) 2','b) 3','c) 2.33','d) 4',NULL,1),(46,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\nInitialize Integer x, y, z\n    Set x = 8, y = 2\n    z = x * y\n    Print z','a) 8','b) 16','c) 2','d) 4',NULL,2),(47,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\n    Initialize Integer a, b, c\n    Set a = 9, b = 2\n    c = a % b\n   Print c\n    z = x * y\n    Print z','a) 1','b) 0','c) 2','d) 4',NULL,1),(48,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\n    Initialize Integer x, y, z\n    Set x = 10, y = 2\n    z = x / y\n    Print z','a) 2','b) 5','c) 10','d) 20',NULL,2),(49,'What will be the output of the following pseudocode?\n     Initialize Integer a, b, c\n     Set a = 11, b = 2\n     c = a - b\n     Print c','a) 2','b) 9','c) 11','d) -9',NULL,2),(50,'Which of the following best defines an algorithm?','a) A sequence of code that performs a specific task.','b) A step-by-step procedure to solve a problem.','c) A graphical user interface design.','d) A storage mechanism for data.\n',NULL,2),(51,'What distinguishes a good algorithm from a poor one?','a) Length of code.','b) Complexity of mathematical formulas used.','c) Efficient problem-solving capability','d) Number of comments in the code.',NULL,3),(52,'Which of the following is a characteristic of a good algorithm?','a) It only works for small input sizes.','b) It relies heavily on trial and error.','c) It is difficult for others to understand.','d) It can handle various input sizes efficiently.',NULL,4),(53,'What role does pseudocode play in algorithm design?','a) It is used to execute code directly','b) It represents a specific programming language.','c) It provides a high-level description of the algorithm\'s logic.','d) It helps design user interfaces.',NULL,3),(54,'What does efficiency refer to in the context of algorithms?','a) The speed at which the algorithm executes.','b) The complexity of the problem being solved.','c) The number of lines of code in the algorithm','d) The amount of memory used by the algorithm.',NULL,1),(55,'Imagine a program needs to find the smallest number in a list of integers. Which of the following best describes this search algorithm?','a) Start with the first number and compare it to every other number.\r\nIf it\'s smaller, keep it as the smallest. Repeat until all numbers are compared.','b) Ask the user to manually identify the smallest number.','c) Add all the numbers together and then divide by the number of integers\r\n(average number).','d) Randomly pick a number and assume it\'s the smallest. If you find a smaller one later, replace it.',NULL,1),(56,'Why is it important for an algorithm to have clear and well-defined steps?','a) It makes the code shorter.','b) It allows for easy execution of code.','c) It helps avoid ambiguity and errors.','d) It increases the complexity of the problem.',NULL,3),(57,'Which of the following statements about algorithms is true?','a) Algorithms are only used in computer science.','b) Algorithms always produce correct results.','c) Algorithms cannot be modified once created.','d) Algorithms can solve a wide range of problems.',NULL,4),(58,'What does the term \"scalability\" mean in the context of algorithms?','a) The ability of an algorithm to adapt to different programming languages.','b) The ability of an algorithm to handle large input sizes efficiently.','c) The ability of an algorithm to execute on different operating systems','d) The ability of an algorithm to solve complex mathematical problems.',NULL,2),(59,' In algorithm design, what does the term \"robustness\" refer to?','a) The ability of an algorithm to handle unexpected inputs or conditions.','b) The efficiency of the algorithm in terms of time and space complexity.','c) The length of the code required to implement the algorithm.','d) The number of comments and documentation in the algorithm code.',NULL,1),(60,'Imagine a program needs to search for a specific word in a large text document. Which of the following best describes this search algorithm?','a) Start at the beginning of the document and read through each\r\nword until the target word is found.','b) Ask the user to manually identify the word in the document.','c) Use a mathematical formula to calculate the position of the word\r\nin the document.','d) Randomly pick a word and assume it\'s the target. If you find the correct\r\nword later, replace it.',NULL,1);
